    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1936-12-30T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1936-12-30T05:00:00-05:00" n="457"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d457">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/13849: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lockhart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-12-30T18:00:00+08:00"
                            >December 30, 1936—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 30—9:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>646. An American newspaper correspondent who returned today from Loyang stated
                    that the impression is general there that the <hi rend="italic">quid pro
                        quo</hi>, in part, for Chiang’s release is the acceptance of most of the
                    points set forth in Chang Hsueh-liang’s circular telegram (see Embassy’s 627,
                    December 20, 5 p.m.). The correspondent also states that young officers have now
                    largely supplanted older men in Chang’s army; that the “feudal dead wood”, as
                    they were described, have (presumably) been dismissed or allowed to resign; that
                    the young officers have been undergoing intensive political and military
                    training for many months and that they now dominate Chang Hsueh-liang. It is
                    entirely possible that this element may have been a dominating factor in Chang’s
                    recent coup. Correspondent reports that the Central Government has an extremely
                    firm hold on Shansi and that the movements of all foreigners in Loyang and
                    thereabouts are closely watched. He reports an extremely strong military line
                    along the Lung-Hai Railway.</p>
                <p>By mail to Tokyo.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lockhart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
